  ('landmine-sumo-deadlift', 'The landmine gives Landmine Sumo Deadlift a constrained arc, reducing some degrees of freedom while still demanding bracing, grip, shoulder control, and lower-body contribution. This makes the drill easier to coach than many free-bar alternatives while still creating a meaningful strength or power problem.', 'Belongs in capacity because the main training stress is wide-stance pull that loads hips, adductors, grip, and trunk without a conventional barbell setup. Keep the phase honest: use low volume and full recovery for Output, progressive load for Capacity, and calm control for Resilience.', 'Place after Prepare & Access and any needed Movement Intelligence. Output variants come before heavy strength or conditioning; Capacity and Resilience variants belong in the main strength or accessory block before late-session fatigue work.', 'Common mistakes are overloading the sleeve, rushing the eccentric, twisting through the low back instead of pivoting, letting the bar drift off its arc, and turning the drill into a conditioning station.', 'Scale by load, range, stance width, kneeling vs standing position, tempo, attachment choice, rep speed, and rest. Progress only when the athlete can keep the same bar path and breathing under every rep.'),
